{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits of retaining or restoring habitat connectivity for butterfly populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on documented studies, habitat connectivity provides several benefits for butterfly populations. Restoring connectivity between habitat patches increased the abundance of multiple butterfly species including Karner blue, high brown fritillary, small pearl-bordered fritillary, marsh fritillary, and regal fritillary (Action 3934). Studies found that common buckeye and variegated fritillary butterflies were more likely to move between connected than unconnected habitat patches (Action 3934). Additionally, grassland strips providing nectar or shelter were more likely to be used by butterfly species than strips with no resources (Action 3934). For population retention, low quality habitat patches that were well connected were more likely to retain Alcon large blue populations than less well connected patches, though connectivity did not affect occupancy of high quality patches (Action 3832). Connectivity also influenced colonization behavior, as common buckeye butterflies were more likely to colonize farther away habitat patches when released on corridors of suitable habitat compared to unsuitable habitat, though this effect was not observed when released close to habitat patches (Action 3832). However, one study found that well connected cleared patches within woodland had similar species richness of butterflies to isolated cleared patches (Action 3832).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3934",
    "3832"
  ]
}

