{
  "query": "What are the benefits for butterflies and moths of reducing or eliminating chemical inputs on farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Reducing or eliminating chemical inputs on farmland provides several documented benefits for butterflies and moths. Studies show that areas not sprayed with herbicides such as glyphosate and fluazifop-P-butyl have greater species richness and higher total abundance of butterflies compared to sprayed areas (Action 3896). Similarly, plants not sprayed with insecticides like Karate Zeon have higher abundance of moth eggs and caterpillars (Action 3896). \n\nGeneral reduction of fertilizer, pesticide, or herbicide use results in greater species richness of adult butterflies and moths, and higher abundance of these species compared to areas with conventional chemical applications (Action 3897). These benefits include increases in both adult butterflies and moths as well as caterpillars (Action 3897). Additionally, unfertilized grassland shows greater species richness of specialist moths compared to fertilized grassland (Action 3897).\n\nConverting to organic farming, which eliminates synthetic chemical inputs, demonstrates that organic arable farms have greater species richness and abundance of butterflies, burnet moths, and all moths than conventionally managed farms (Action 3907). The abundance of butterflies increases with time since farms converted to organic management (Action 3907). When farms convert to organic management, the species richness of large moths and total abundance of large moths can increase within 4 years (Action 3907).\n\nLeaving headlands in fields unsprayed provides additional benefits, with unsprayed headlands showing greater species richness and abundance of butterflies and caterpillars than headlands sprayed with herbicide and insecticide (Action 3898). Butterflies also exhibit behavioral benefits, spending more time feeding and interacting in unsprayed headlands compared to sprayed areas (Action 3898).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3896",
    "3897",
    "3907",
    "3898"
  ]
}

