{
  "query": "What management actions for traditional orchards and vineyards in the USA and Germany have been studied for their effects on butterflies and moths?",
  "relevant_summary": "Two main management actions for traditional orchards and vineyards in the USA and Germany have been studied for their effects on butterflies and moths. For traditional orchards, two studies were conducted - one in the USA and one in Germany - evaluating the effects of maintaining traditional orchards on butterflies and moths (Action 3917). The German study found that managed orchards had similar community composition and species richness of butterflies and burnet moths compared to abandoned orchards, but lower abundance. The USA study found that an unmanaged and partially managed orchard had greater species richness and diversity of leaf-eating arthropods (including caterpillars) than a commercially managed orchard. For vineyards, two studies were conducted - one in the USA and one in Spain - evaluating the effects of managing vineyards to benefit butterflies and moths (Action 3919). The USA study found that grass strips between vine rows had greater species richness of butterflies than vine rows themselves, and that vineyards managed to encourage native plants with rare insecticide use had greater butterfly abundance than conventionally managed vineyards. The Spain study found that vineyards managed with fewer chemicals had greater butterfly species richness than conventionally managed vineyards.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3917",
    "3919"
  ]
}

