{
  "query": "Over what timeframes have butterfly communities been observed to respond to grassland management changes like abandonment or restoration?",
  "relevant_summary": "Butterfly communities have been observed to respond to grassland management changes across various timeframes ranging from months to decades. Following grassland abandonment from grazing, studies found responses occurring within 2-9 years (action 3956), with one study showing butterfly density was higher in grasslands where grazing ceased 2-9 years ago than those abandoned >10 years ago. For grasslands abandoned >5-20 years, results varied by species richness and abundance depending on the specific timeframe (action 3956). After mowing cessation, responses were documented from as early as 1-3 years to over 25 years, with studies showing grasslands abandoned for 1-6 years had increased woodland and hedgerow butterflies but decreased grassland species (action 3957). One study found heath fritillary abundance was similar in grasslands abandoned for around 6 years compared to annually mown grasslands, but grasslands abandoned for >25 years had lower abundance (action 3957). For grassland restoration from arable land, butterfly communities developed over 10 years after establishment, with communities becoming increasingly similar to existing high-quality grasslands over this period (action 3929). Studies showed species richness was higher on grasslands created <10 years ago than on grasslands created >20 years ago (action 3929). In prairie restoration, one study found greater abundance of Fender's blue eggs in prairies restored 5-10 years ago compared to those restored 1-2 years ago (action 3943). A controlled study spanning 6 years showed that after abandonment from both grazing and mowing, butterfly communities became dominated by generalist species and species with fewer generations per year (actions 3956, 3957).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3956",
    "3957",
    "3929",
    "3943"
  ]
}

