{
  "query": "What does the evidence show about the timeframe for butterfly and moth population response to woodland coppicing or clearing?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence shows specific timeframes for butterfly and moth population responses to woodland coppicing and clearing. For woodland coppicing, butterfly abundance was higher in woodland coppiced two, two-four, five-seven or 12-15 years ago compared to woodland coppiced 5-11 or greater than 15 years ago (Action 3939). Species richness of butterflies was greater in woodland coppiced two years ago than woodland coppiced greater than 15 years ago (Action 3939). Pearl-bordered fritillary and small pearl-bordered fritillary populations were more likely to persist for up to 20 years in coppiced woodland than in mature conifer woodland (Action 3939). For forest clearing, the abundance of butterflies declined over the first three years after clearing (Action 3938). Patches cleared 2-4 years ago had greater abundance of heath fritillary than patches cleared 7-11 years ago or patches in their first year after clearance (Action 3938). Species richness of butterflies declined over the first three years after clearing (Action 3938). Pearl-bordered fritillary and small pearl-bordered fritillary populations were more likely to persist for up to 20 years in woodlands with larger areas of young plantations or coppicing than in mature woodland (Action 3941). In naturally regenerating forests, butterfly abundance and species richness was highest 12-25 years after felling (Action 3876).",
